data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression-tree building needed — conditionals work directly inside the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate property names across complex types are now uniquified.** Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` will get auto-disambiguated names (e.g. `Street1`), generating a migration that renames columns. Pin the existing names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now include the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to `BillingAddress_City` — it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. Pin it if you need the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your `MyLogger` won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection,
    DbCommand command,
    DbContext context,
    Guid commandId,
    Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL for safe logging
{
    // logCommandText has constants redacted; use for logs
    // command.CommandText has the actual SQL
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.

---

**Summary:** The expression-tree rewrite is the biggest win — it eliminates significant complexity. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes. After making these changes, generate a new migration to verify no unexpected column renames sneak in from the complex-type naming changes.
